nted books, photographs, and Gramophone records. She discusses such issues as architectural restoration, the modern history of typography, the uncanny power of the photographic image, and the authority of recorded sound. She also shows the extent to which different media shaped the modern image of the ancient repertory, an image that gave rise to conflicting notions not only of musical performance but of the very idea of music history.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aGregorian chantsxHistory and criticism. 7aMUSIC / Genres & Styles / Classical.2bisacsh  abenedictine order.  aeuropean music.  afrench culture.  afrench gothic revival.  afrench monks.  agregorian chant.  agregorian restoration.  agregorian revival.  alost liturgy.  amodern concepts.  amonastic choir.  anew perspective.  apostrevolutionary.  apublic commodities.  arebuilding.  arestoration.  aromantic origins.  asolesmes.  atechnological development.  atradition.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Package Archive Pre-2000z97831106353480 cprintz978052021008040uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/9780520919617?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520919617423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520919617/original  a978-3-11-063534-8  University of California Press Package Archive Pre-2000b2000  aEBA_FAO  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-UCY